{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":5023,"record_hash":"sha256:b1c315e8a02ae7b117ff411ab9cd41395e2cde9569e946c5b65c9bc36c999849","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:14:32.903Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"::code-comment{title=\"[P2] Git hash labels can preserve affixed secrets\" body=\"`is_git_object_id()` preserves the whole candidate when it finds a labelled 40/64-hex subrange. Since `-`, `/`, and `=` are candidate bytes and accepted hash boundaries, a value like `commit <sha>-<random-secret>` can be treated as a Git object ID even though the random suffix is stored too. Require the candidate to end at the hash, or otherwise preserve only the hash-shaped part.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=225 end=232 priority=2 confidence=0.86}\n\n::code-comment{title=\"[P2] UUID-shaped secrets can bypass redaction\" body=\"UUID-ish values are preserved before considering field context, so a UUID-shaped secret under `api_key`, `token`, or `secret` would be stored verbatim. A small fix would let sensitive field names override the UUID/timestamp allowlist, or only preserve UUIDs for known ID-like fields.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=110 end=116 priority=2 confidence=0.78}\n\n::code-comment{title=\"[P3] Slash-inclusive candidates can over-redact paths\" body=\"Including `/` in candidate bytes catches slashy base64, but it also makes long paths scan as one candidate. Some realistic path strings can cross the entropy threshold and lose useful transcript context. This may be an acceptable POC tradeoff, but it is still worth knowing about.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=119 end=123 priority=3 confidence=0.72}\n\nWe’re closer to equilibrium: no new P1s this round. The cleanup-only reviewer is down to small P3s (`RedactedValue`, `is_obvious_non_secret`, loop style), so the remaining meaningful behavior questions are mostly policy tradeoffs around allowlists. Targeted local checks passed: `cargo test -p but-agentlog redaction --lib` and `cargo clippy -p but-agentlog --all-targets --no-deps`.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:14:32.903Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}